Hi there!

After the update, I've encountered performance issues. Our project relies heavily on **custom variants**. Previously, we used the **addVariant** API to add them, which kept the generated CSS lightweight and didn‚Äôt slow down the browser.

Now, when using the new approach with **@custom-variant**, we experience severe slowdowns, especially in large projects. The issue is particularly noticeable in Chrome, and in Safari, it's even worse.

I‚Äôve concluded that the problem lies specifically in the CSS, as the rest of the code remains unchanged. Below, I‚Äôll show an example of how the generated CSS looked before and how it looks now.

**_Version 3 (Old Approach)_**:
```
addVariant('dropdown-open', [
  ({ modifySelectors, separator }) => {
    modifySelectors(({ className }) => {
      return `.dropdown.open > .${e(`dropdown-open${separator}${className}`)}`;
    });
  },
  ({ modifySelectors, separator }) => {
    modifySelectors(({ className }) => {
      return `.dropdown.open > .dropdown-toggle .${e(`dropdown-open${separator}${className}`)}`;
    });
  },
  ({ modifySelectors, separator }) => {
    modifySelectors(({ className }) => {
      return `.dropdown.open > .dropdown-menu > .${e(`dropdown-open${separator}${className}`)}`;
    });
  }
]);
```
Generated CSS:
```
.dropdown.open > .dropdown-open\:opacity-100 {
    opacity: 1;
}
```

**_Version 4 (@custom-variant)_**:
```
@custom-variant dropdown-open {
  &.dropdown-menu.open,
  .dropdown.open > &,
  .dropdown.open > .dropdown-toggle &,
  .dropdown.open > .dropdown-menu > & {
    @slot;
  }
}
```
Generated CSS:
```
.dropdown-open\:opacity-100 {
    &.dropdown-menu.open, 
    .dropdown.open > &, 
    .dropdown.open > .dropdown-toggle &, 
    .dropdown.open > .dropdown-menu > & {
        opacity: 100%;
    }
}
```

I know this example is a bit complicated, but despite that, everything worked fine in the old version. I also noticed that previously, classes were generated separately, while now they are merged into one large rule.

There can be quite a lot of such custom variants in our project, and as a result, this significantly affects performance.

Maybe I‚Äôm doing something wrong, and there‚Äôs a better way to define variants? If anyone has faced a similar issue, I‚Äôd really appreciate any help!

Closes #16035

In v3 it was possible to unset a specific color namespace by setting doing something like this:

```js
export default {
  theme: {
    extend: {
      colors: {
        red: null,
      },
    },
  },
}
```

This pattern would crash in v4 right now due to the theme access function not being able to work on the red property being a `null`. This PR fixes this crash.

However it leaves the behavior as-is for now so that the red namespace _defined via CSS will still be accessible_. This is technically different from v3 but fixing this would be more work as we only allow unsetting top-level namespaces in the interop layer (via the non-`extend`-theme-object). I would recommend migrating to the v4 API for doing these partial namespace resets if you want to get rid of the defaults in v4:

```css
@theme {
  --color-red-*: initial;
}
```

## Test plan

The crash was mainly captured via the test in `compat/config.test.ts` but I've added two more tests across the different levels of abstractions so that it's clear what `null` should be doing.

This PR fixes an issue where if you use `@import url(‚Ä¶);` _after_ the `@import "tailwindcss";`, then invalid CSS is being generated.

This is because the `@import "tailwindcss";` directive is being replaced with the actual generated CSS variables, utilities, etc. but the `@import url(‚Ä¶);` is kept as-is (Tailwind CSS doesn't handle these). This means that in the final CSS the `@import url(‚Ä¶)` could be in the middle of the generated CSS which is invalid.

```css
/* Invalid: */
@import "tailwindcss";
@import url('https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Roboto&display=swap');
```

```css
/* Valid: */
@import "tailwindcss";
@import url('https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Roboto&display=swap');
```

While the above examples should both work from a CSS perspective, this PR makes sure to hoist the `@import url(‚Ä¶);` rules. All non-external imports will be inlined already.

Once this PR is merged, both these situations are valid:
```css
/* Valid: */
@import "tailwindcss";
@import url('https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Roboto&display=swap');
```

```css
/* Valid: */
@import "tailwindcss";
@import url('https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Roboto&display=swap');
```

In order to do this correctly, we also have to make sure that the license comment and `@charset` is in the correct spot.

### Test plan

- Added a simple unit test
- Added an integration test

CSS custom @keyframes are not being populated when they are imported from other files.

**What version of Tailwind CSS are you using?**

v4.0.3

**What build tool (or framework if it abstracts the build tool) are you using?**

@tailwindcss/vite@4.0.3

**What version of Node.js are you using?**

v23.6.0

**What browser are you using?**

Chrome, Safari

**What operating system are you using?**

macOS

**Reproduction**

```css
/* main.css */
@import "tailwindcss";
@import "./animation.css";
```

```css
/* animation.css */
@theme {
  --animate-fade-in: fade-in 0.6s ease-in;

  @keyframes fade-in {
    0%: {
      opacity: 0;
    }

    100%: {
      opacity: 1;
    }
  }
}
```

**Describe your issue**

I'm building an animation like plugin for tw v4. The animation name and class are being populated as expected but the animation is not loaded by the browser even tho when the css is there.

